headline: What's driving the latest bout of AI deals? Analyst answers.
summary: Moor Insights & Strategy founder, CEO, and chief analyst Patrick Moorhead and Futurum CEO Daniel Newman discuss the AI milestones that could push Big Tech companies and hyperscalers even farther, including meeting compute capacity and demands, amid the latest round of artificial intelligence deals and partnerships. Also catch Daniel Newman and Patrick Moorhead weigh in on whether bubbles are forming in the AI trade. headline: AI companies are looking 'sturdy' as 'little bubbles' form
summary: As major tech companies execute massive AI partnerships — namely Advanced Micro Devices' (AMD) deal with OpenAI (OPAI.PVT), and Nvidia's (NVDA) own business dealings with OpenAI, Intel (INTC), and Alibaba (BABA) — is Wall Street skeptical about a market bubble forming? Moor Insights & Strategy founder, CEO, and chief analyst Patrick Moorhead and Futurum CEO Daniel Newman chat with Josh Lipton about the "sturdiness" of Big Tech names than compared to the previous Dot-Com Bubble. headline: Arduino deal plays into scaling up Qualcomm's AI edge, exec. says
summary: Qualcomm (QCOM) announced plans to acquire Italian hardware and software developer Arduino, allowing the AI semiconductor manufacturer to lean heavier into the robotics market. Qualcomm group general manager of automotive and industrial & embedded IoT (Internet of Things) Nakul Duggal sits down with Julie Hyman and Yahoo Finance tech editor Dan Howley to discuss how this deal will expand Qualcomm's ability to scale, particularly its edge computing capabilities. headline: Carillon Technologies Appoints Jim Cathey to Board of Directors
summary: Carillon Technologies, a developer of advanced technologies for both commercial and government applications, today announced the appointment of Jim Cathey to its Board of Directors. Mr. Cathey brings decades of global leadership experience in the technology and communications sectors, with a proven record of driving growth, strategic partnerships, and innovation in satellite and advanced communications markets.

headline: Qualcomm buys open-source electronics firm Arduino
summary: SAN FRANCISCO (Reuters) -Qualcomm on Tuesday said it has acquired Arduino, an Italian not-for-profit firm that makes hardware and software for developing prototypes of robots and other electronic gadgets.  San Diego-based Qualcomm is a major supplier of chips at the heart of mobile phones but has been expanding into other fields such as connected vehicles, wireless earphones, laptop computers and industrial machines.  With the Arduino deal, it will acquire an open-source platform with more than 33 million developers.
